Name.actor: Dodd, Jimmie|~|Montoya, Alex, $d 1907-1970|~|Alaniz, Rico|~|Robertson, Dale, $d 1923-2013|~|Sheldon, Gene, $d 1909-1982|~|Brodus, Tex|~|Day, Dennis, $d 1916-1988|~|Dominguez, Joe
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Jimmie Dodd, Dennis Day, Dale Robertson and cast members in Golden Girl
Description.caption: Mitzi Gaynor, Dale Robertson, Dennis Day, James Barton in "Golden Girl"Produced by George JesselDirected by Lloyd Bacon20th Century-Fox Printed in U.S.A.Copyright 1951, 20th Century-Fox Film Corp.
Description.note: Actor Joe Dominguez has also been credited in films as, Jose Dominguez and Joe Dominquez.|~|Several cast members appear in this photograph, taken from a scene in the film, "Golden Girl," (l to r):  Jimmie Dodd (seated in foreground), Dennis Day, possibly Gene Sheldon (with banjo), possibly Tex Brodus (with accordion), an unidentified 'Bandit' cast member, Joe Dominguez, Dale Robertson, Alex Montoya and Rico Alaniz.The unidentified 'Bandit' may possibly be either Charles Rivero, George Navarro or Paul Regas, all of which were also credited as 'Bandit' in the film. Actor Paul Burke was also credited as 'Bandit,' but would have been too young and bears no resemblance to the unidentified actor. Also, there are two others actors, Robert Cherry and Danny Jackson, credited in the film as 'Band Member,' besides the three that are previously mentioned and possibly identified (Jimmie Dodd, Gene Sheldon and Tex Brodus).

The boxer went on to nearly 30 appearances (as an actor) in films throughout the 1940's.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Cabaret group, The Revuers, featuring Judy Holliday, Adolph Green, Betty Comden and Alvin Hammer on the set of Greenwich Village
Description.caption: A Scene from the 20th Century-Fox Production "Greenwich Village"
Description.note: The scene depicted in this photograph does not appear in the film, "Greenwich Village." The members of The Revuers, however, do appear briefly in a party scene in the apartment of actress Vivian Blaine's character, 'Bonnie Watson'. Two of The Revuers, Alvin Hammer and Adolph Green, are also seen singing the song,   "When You Wore a Tulip and I Wore a Big Red Rose," alongside actors, B. S. Pully, Don Ameche and William Bendix.|~|From the AFI listing: The picture marked the screen debut of The Revuers, a cabaret group featuring Judy Holliday (who is billed as Judith Tuvim on the CBCS), Betty Comden, Adolph Green and Alvin Hammer. Although a 16 Feb 1944 Hollywood Reporter news indicated that The Revuers' "satiric sketch of a Shubert operetta" had been purchased by the studio for their debut, their sequence was cut from the finished picture, and modern sources note that the group appears only in the party scene at "Bonnie Watson's" apartment. After the group broke up, Holliday became a well-known Broadway and motion picture comedienne and won an Academy Award for Best Actress for "Born Yesterday." Comden and Green became a popular songwriting team whose films included "On the Town."|~|Actress/singer and future Oscar-winner, Judy Holliday (birth name: Judith Tuvim), appears here in her first film, "Greenwich Village," credited only as a member of the cabaret group, The Revuers. Most of her scenes, including the scene depicted in this photograph, did not make the film's final cut.|~|Actress/singer/songwriter, Betty Comden, is credited as, 'Hat Check Girl,' and as a member of the cabaret group, The Revuers in the film, "Greenwich Village." Most of the Revuers' scenes, including the one depicted in this photograph, did not make the film's final cut.

AltTitle.uniform: Guilt Of Janet Ames, The  (Motion picture)
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Rosalind Russell, Sid Caesar and Melvyn Douglas in The Guilt of Janet Ames
Description.note: From the AFI listing: A May, 1946 Hollywood Reporter news item noted that producer Virginia Van Upp's husband, Ralph Nelson, also a producer, was set to work on the film, but his contribution to the released film has not been confirmed. Various news items in HR indicate that production on the film was interrupted many times throughout the summer and fall of 1946, and that Van Upp and Charles Vidor, the film's original director, were embroiled in a bitter dispute about the script. In April, 1946, Vidor, while working on the film "Gilda," sued Columbia for termination of his contract. The suit was part of a long-standing dispute with studio executives and personnel that spanned many years. Production on the film was suspended for approximately two weeks in mid-August, 1946, after, according to a HR news item, Van Upp collapsed on the set. Van Upp was removed from the picture, and a HR news item suggested that her troubles stemmed from player commitments that forced her to begin filming the picture before the script was completed. Helen Deutsch took over Van Upp's production chores and, during the two-week production shutdown, supervised a series of script revisions and additions. A September 18, 1946 HR news item, noted that Vidor then became involved in a major dispute with Deutsch, whose supervision he was reportedly refusing. On September 24, 1946, HR printed a statement issued by Columbia production chief Harry Cohn, in which Cohn stated "emphatically and clearly that Miss Helen Deutsch is the producer of the picture and that Mr. Charles Vidor is not." The statement also reveals that Deutsch had asked to be relieved of her duties, and that Cohn insisted that she remain on the film. Vidor's suit against Columbia went to trial in December, 1946, at which time, according to HR, Vidor testified that Cohn made derogatory remarks to him and vilified his wife, Doris Warner. According to a September, 1947 HR news item, Vidor lost his suit against Columbia, and Columbia then sued Vidor.

Title: Phil Silvers and Dick Haymes in Diamond Horseshoe
Description.caption: Betty Grable and Dick Haymes in Billy Rose's "Diamond Horseshoe" with Phil Silvers, William Gaxton, Beatrice Kay, Carmen Cavallaro, Willie Solar, Margaret Dumont. Written for the Screen by George Seaton. Produced by William Perlberg. In Technicolor.
Description.note: Also billed as "Billy Rose's Diamond Horseshoe", several contemporary and modern sources refer to this film as "Diamond Horseshoe". According to information in the Twentieth Century-Fox Records of the Legal Department, located at the UCLA Arts - Special Collections Library, entertainment entrepreneur Billy Rose sold Twentieth Century-Fox the rights to use the name of his famed nightclub, The Diamond Horseshoe, for this film for $75,000.

Name.producer: Levine, Joseph E.|~|Irwin, James R.|~|Byrd, Richard Evelyn, $d 1888-1957
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Explorers and vehicles in a scene from Antarctica expedition documentary film Discovery
Description.caption: Admiral Richard E. Byrd's Mighty DISCOVERY. SEE...supermen of tomorrow invading the super-world of yesterday. SEE...a hidden world defying invasion. SEE...the earth's core caught by a dragnet of ice. Released through Film Classics, Inc.
Description.note: "Discovery" was a documentary film made (and narrated) by Rear Admiral Richard Evelyn Byrd, the pioneering naval officer, aviator and polar explorer. Apparently the footage for the film was shot on an earlier expedition of Antarctica (from 1933 to 1935). Another film, "Little America" (1935 Paramount), also depicts this expedition.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Animated sequence from Dom
Description.caption: La Maison
Description.note: "Dom" (Polish for House) is a 12-minute 1958 Polish short film that combines live action with various animation techniques, such as stop motion, cut-out animation and pixilation. "Dom" was nominated for a 1959 BAFTA Film Award, in the category for Best Animated Film, but lost to "The Violinist".|~|Actress Ligia Branice, who makes a brief appearance in the film, was credited as Ligia Borowczyk, the wife of director Walerian Borowczyk.

Title: Ben Ali Gator in Dance of the Hours sequence from Fantasia
Description.caption: Tail spin - Ben Ali Gator gives a lift to his oversized dancing partner in "Dance of the Hours" from Walt Disney's animated classic "Fantasia." In color by Technicolor and featuring a new digitally rerecorded Dolby stereophonic sound track, "Fantasia" is re-released by Buena Vista. Irwin Kostal conducted, based on the original sound track by Leopold Stokowski.
Description.note: Original film artwork created circa 1940; these stills are from the 1990 re-release.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Pastoral Symphony and Dance of the Hours sequences from Fantasia
Description.caption: Top: A mother unicorn protects her young from the raging storm in Beethoven's "Pastoral Sympathy" sequence of Walt Disney's animated classic "Fantasia." Below: Mlle. Upanova and a ballet corps of alligators perform Amilcare Ponchielli's "Dance of the Hours." Re-released on the occasion of its 50th Anniversary, "Fantasia" boasts a completely restored and enhanced print utilizing the original Leopold Stowkowski-conducted score. In color by Technicolor, "Fantasia" is re-released by Buena Vista Pictures Distribution.
Description.note: Original film artwork created circa 1940; these stills are from the 1990 re-release.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Night on Bald Mountain and Sorcerer's Apprentice scenes from Fantasia
Description.caption: Top: Chernabog, lord of evil and death, plays host to demons, spirits and skeletons on the witches' Sabbath, in this frightening interpretation of Modeste Moussorgsky's "Night on Bald Mountain," from Walt Disney's animated classic "Fantasia." Below: Meddling in magic makes for a miserable Mickey, in Paul Dukas' "The Sorcerer's Apprentice." Re-released on the occasion of its 50th anniversary, "Fantasia" boasts a completely restored and enhanced print utilizing the original Leopold Stokowski-conducted score. In color by Techicolor, "Fantasia" is re-released by Buena Vista Pictures Distribution.
Description.note: Original film artwork created circa 1940; these stills are from the 1990 re-release.

Title: Images of accompanying materials for 1990 re-release of Disney's Fantasia

Name.distributor: RKO Radio Pictures|~|Buena Vista Film Distribution Co.
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Pastoral Symphony and Dance of the Hours sequences from Fantasia
Description.caption: Top: The magnificent black Pegasus and his snow-white mate gambol through the air with their young entourage, to the music of Beethoven's "Pastoral Symphony" in Walt Disney's animated classic "Fantasia." Below: Beasts in the ballet include a prancing pachyderm and graceful alligator, stepping to the strains of Amilcare Ponchielli's "Dance of the Hours." Re-released on the occasion of its 50th anniversary, "Fantasia" boasts a completely restored and enhanced print utilizing the original Leopold Stokowski-conducted score. In color by Technicolor, "Fantasia" is re-released by Buena Vista Pictures Distribution.
Description.note: Original film artwork created circa 1940; these stills are from the 1990 re-release.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Ben Turpin publicity photograph used to promote film, The Golden Age of Comedy
Description.note: The 1958 film, "The Golden Age of Comedy," chronicles the variety of comedic styles and talent at the height of Hollywood's silent era. The film was culled from 2,000 reels of Mack Sennett and Hal Roach short film comedies and divided into eight acts with a prologue and finale. This photograph was taken from a scene from the 1926 silent film, "A Blonde's Revenge," starring Ben Turpin. Although a well-known publicity photograph of actor Ben Turpin, it does not appear in "The Golden Age of Comedy," nor does any film scene from "A Blonde's Revenge." Turpin, however, is quite well-represented with other clips in the film, within the section entitled, "Act V - The Great Actor."
AltTitle.other: The Blonde's Revenge|~|A Blonde's Revenge|~|Fools for Scandal

Title: William Gaxton, Almira Sessions, Mary Roche and Victor Moore in The Heat's On
Description.caption: The Heat's On starring Mae West - Victor Moore - William Gaxton with Lester Allen - Alan Dinehart - Lloyd Bridges - Hazel Scott and Xavier Cugat and His Orchestra - Directed by Gregory Ratoff - A Columbia Picture
Description.note: "The Heat's On," is the only film that Mary Roche is credited for as an actress. Future film credits were as 'hair stylist' for many productions, including the film, "On The Waterfront." She has also been credited as, Mary Roche-Faye. The LoC Authorities file lists her as, Mary Roche.
